Islam can be French? 
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state. 
Roger Bootle, Deloitte 
Some readers will be attracted by this new book, admirers of the author's latest book, "why the French do not like the headscarf" (2006), an elegant and well documented on an issue that has divided and concerned the country for 15 years and whose effects are still being felt today. 
The last book by Mr Bowen presents a much broader and more ambitious. 
Good anthropologist, it does not only wishes to know what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is happening in the country. 
He spent many months in mosques, schools and institutions that provide now in France this queM. Bozen calls "spaces" for 5m-6m Muslims. 
He knows very well listen and reproduce the debates between teachers and students on issues that concern them most. 
A Muslim should marry in a mosque or city hall (or both)? 
The evolution and The rights of homosexuals should be taught to young Muslims? 
A Muslim woman can marry a non-Muslim? 
A Muslim can use a banking system based on interests to obtain a loan? 
These are practical problems, he says, which are the daily lot, rather than the political dramas that concern the media. 
The author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, all unknown to the general public, except perhaps Tariq Ramadan, a Muslim Arab born in Switzerland. 
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how to be both a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society. 
They do not push the debate until the end. 
Lesconservateurs do not believe in the idea of a French or European Islam. 
The Intellectuals and activists who have been interviewed by Mr. Bowen are generally in agreement with their counterparts lawyers of a Sunni Islam purist associated with Saudi Arabia that today, are a small part of Muslims in Europe. 
M Bowen believes that the values of Muslims and secularism of French could be compatible. 
But a compromise can be achieved only with the efforts of each camp. 
He wondered how the French politicians (and the intellectual elite guardian if virulent of secularism) are really committed to pluralism. 
According to him, Muslims have not been spoiled, compared to Catholics, Protestants and Jews who have also had to make historic compromises with the secular republicanism. 
Rather than a growing pragmatism, it detects a "narrowness of key values ". 
Islam can be French? After reading this book, one is tempted to say "yes, but not yet." 
The view The world's darkest 
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatic than any other place on The planet. 
The ice is melting at an alarming rate, taking with it a life that cannot survive elsewhere. 
Oil, gas, shipments and new fisheries sail in open waters, with diplomats, lawyers and now writers in their wake. 
In "on a thin layer of ice," Richard Ellis, writer and illustrator, painted a natural history of the symbol of the far north, the polar bear. 
Who knows the history and complicated political of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who were their evidence in hunting polar bears. 
The meeting of Admiral Nelson, then courageous aspiring 14 years who had to fight the tip of his musket, is certainly a myth, but the rest is true. 
The young cubs, captured while they swam alongside their mother, just killed, were caught and sent to zoos and circuses. 
At the beginning of the twentieth century, a show celebrates 75 bears At the same time. 
Even today, the dimensions of a zoo are still generally a millionth of the surface necessary for an adult in liberté. Climate is rarely mentioned: a polar bear living in Singapore became green because of algae that grew in its thick fur. 
Click here for more information! 
Mr. Ellis tells the stories of other writers and historians and is often on the threat posed by hunters on the survival of species. 
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, the killings continue in Greenland and Canada where hunters by helicopter and Inuit Indians in motoski use fusilsd "powerful assault to hunt their game. 
Ironically, it is in the most northerly waters of these two nations of hunting that ice will remain the longest. 
In his new book, "after the ice ", Alun Anderson, a former editor of new Scientist, offers a clear summary and frightening science of the Arctic and a fascinating glimpse of what may be the future there. 
Not that scientists have all the answers. 
Neither the atmosphéristes nor oceanographers cannot tell exactly the speed of change. 
It is not for lack of trying. 
Late nineteenth and early twentieth, travel pioneers of Fridtjof Nansen gave the initial information on the melting of the ice cap. 
The submarines in the Cold War were then mapped changes of relief sous-celle-ci. 
The Surveillance satellites and probes placed on icebergs are a great help, but most of the work is done by men hardened, camping in the cold. 
Mr Anderson looking at the world extraordinary and tiny system dependent on the Arctic ice, formed by the nets of brackish water pressure by freezing. 
But the bear mentioned above the wonders microscopic contained in the ice, everything will be lost with the disappearance of summer ice, scheduled between 2013 and 2050. 
"In a few months, this may be our turn" 
The Marines, among the 6, 000 people who have laid wreaths on the graves in Arlington 
The first class De "Angello Robinson, 19, made a trip of seven hours by bus to file a simple wreath on the grave of a soldier that he had never met. 
For him and the other Marines who made the trip to Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina at Arlington National Cemetery to decorate the graves, this day was devoted to salute the men and women who, one day, were in their place. 
In a few months, where we will be sent, we will be in their place, Robinson said about the fallen soldiers. 
If this happened to me, I would like someone to do the same thing for me, that is why I just trying to show respect. 
It was one of the 6, 000 volunteers to be gathered Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans, in different sections of the cemetery of Arlington Ceremony. 
In 1992, Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company to Harrington, Maine, launched the commemoration and others have decided to decorate several hundreds of graves in the cemetery of Arlington Ceremony. 
Now, to continue a tradition of 18 years, Morrill and his wife Karen, each year the journey, stopping in different cities on their way to organize the commemorations in honour of the military and victims of terrorism. 
The Worcester have also founded a non-profit association, Wreaths Across America (Wreaths Across America), which aims to promote the event in all other states. 
This year, volunteers have placed more than 16 000 wreaths on the graves of the cemetery of Arlington, around the Pentagon, on the graves of the cemetery Fayetteville National cemetery enArkansas, in the Battery Park in New York City and on the site of the memorial to the victims of United Airlines Flight 93 Shanksville, Pennsylvania. 
For the second consecutive year, the Walmart Foundation has given more than $150 000 to buy and carry the crowns. 
Charleen Hunt, 70, of Westminster, said that she had made the trip to Arlington in honour of her husband, a career military died. 
Although her husband is not buried at Arlington, Hunt said that for her, this gesture was a way to thank those who had sacrificed. 
It is a small gesture that civilians can do to support our troops, she said. 
It is like visiting a family tomb. 
Emmitouflée in several layers of warm clothing, volunteers walked between the lawns and hills tracts of the cemetery. 
The volunteers have chosen graves old, dating from the First and Second World War, as well as the Vietnam War, because they are not as often visited that new graves, organizers said. 
The mood was optimistic, while children played and couples were held by the hand, wearing the crowns of pine costs on the graves grey. 
Each round crown had a dark green colour, with a small red butterfly knot on the top. 
Nearby, were silent on Section 60, where most of the veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried. 
The United Service Organizations gave 1, 000 crowns to decorate the section but the sour mood of current wars filled the area. 
Individuals without hiding, others prayed and families and friends supported in the cold air. 
Some read aloud the names engraved in stone while others looked to see small black and white information cards, stuck in the wetland for those whose tomb had not yet been completed. 
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers in tears, on the grave of her son. 
It is part of Zanesfield, Ohio and had led eight hours to come to collect on the tomb of Marine Sergeant GunneryDavid Shane Spicer, died in combat in July. 
No one should never forget thanks to what we are free... My son has paid for it, she said. 
"Long after I have disappeared, I want someone to remember him." 
A U.S. citizen arrested by the Cuban authorities 
The Cuban government has arrested an American citizen who disseminated mobile phones and laptop computers in the country, said the services of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs American. 
The citizen, which has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda. 
The company is working on projects for clients such as the U. S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank. 
The consular authorities as well as the U. S. Interest Section in Havana trying to access the inmate who was arrested on 5 December. 
The specific charges have not been made public, although under Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor may be arrested under the pretext of being "dangerous ". 
All the so-called revolutionary activities, including protests moderate and critical writings, entail the risk of arrest. 
The anti-government graffiti and speeches are regarded as serious crimes. 
Cuba has a community of bloggers increasingly large, conducted by Yoani Sánchez, popular commentator who writes often about how are husband and are followed and harassed by government agents. 
Sánchez has made several requests to leave the country to receive rewards but authorisations have always been denied. 
The detention of an American citizen may increase tensions between the communist government of brothers in Cuba and the Obama administration that pursues a "soft" approach to improve relations with the island. 
The announcement of the arrest was first reported by the New York Times, Friday evening. 
The new American policy insists that the Cuban government advance by concrete steps, such as releasing political prisoners and create more space for the opposition, so that the U.S. to reciprocate. 
Mobile phones and laptops are permitted to Cuba, although consumer goods and desired in a country or the average salary of an employee is $15 per month. 
Only this year, the Cuban government has granted to ordinary citizens the right to buy mobile phones; they are mainly used for text messages or for a 15 - minute conversation which corresponds to a day of salary. 
On the island, the use of the Internet is extremely limited. 
It is available in luxury hotels and for foreign visitors in the country, as well as in some government buildings, such as universities. 
The Cubans wishing to connect often must provide their name to the government. 
Access to many Web sites is restricted. 
The detention of an American in Cuba is rare. 
Most of the few American imprisoned in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug trafficking, says Gloria Berbena, press officer with the U. S. Interests Section in Havana. 
Berbena said she could not provide more information on the arrest. 
The arrest and detention are a big mistake. 
An activity that, in any other open society, would be permitted - distribute free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, "said Jose Miguel Vivanco, Americas program director of the group Human Rights Watch, which has recently published a report severe on freedoms in Cuba, called" new Castro, even Cuba ", referring to the installation of Raul Castro as leader of the country to replace Fidel, his older brother ill. 
According to Vivanco, an accused is often arrested, tried and imprisoned on the same day. 
He said that any solution would probably be policy and that the Cuban government often causes a negative reaction in the United States, when the two countries begin to initiate a dialogue. 
The Pakistani authorities prevented a plot to send men in Afghanistan 
Saturday, the Pakistani authorities have identified an organization supposed to prepare a plot to send five men of Northern Virginia in Afghanistan in order to kill American troops, saying they hoped that this case would disassemble an important network of recruiters of terrorists scouring the Internet in search of young men radicalized. 
Investigators said they hunted a personality insurgente hidden, known as Saifullah who invited these men in Pakistan after having discovered when one of them has commented approving the waves terrorists on the YouTube video site on the Internet. 
Arrived in Pakistan, these men were guided by Saifullah who tried to help them to reach the remote area of the tribal belt of Pakistan, home of al-Qaida and its terrorist training camps. 
But a representative of the secret service Pakistanis who has been informed of the case said Saturday that Saifullah had failed to convince the al-Qaeda commanders that these men were not involved in the conspiracy of the CIA to infiltrate the terrorist network. 
As a result, they have been isolated for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the mountains banned northeast become a haven of terrorism. 
They were seen as undercover agents. 
That is why they were rejected, said a representative of the authorities who spoke on condition of anonymity because of the confidential nature of the case. 
The representative of the authorities said that the men were determined and that they were always trying to obtain the necessary approvals for the entry into the camps al-Qaeda when they were arrested by the forces of Pakistani law. 
The case of these five men - who remain in Pakistan and who are interviewed by the FBI - insist on the crucial role of recruiters in the identification of potential terrorists and perhaps more important, in the determination of people who trust. 
Since the attacks of 11 September 2001, the U.S. secret services have been a priority for infiltrate men in the al-Qaeda network. 
The organization Recruiters play the role of firewalls, refusing entry to those who do not show a serious commitment and those who may be spies. 
According to analysts, the American potential recruits are studied closely by al-Qaeda. 
But they are also very attractive to the group because of their potential access to American targets and their value propagandaire. 
However Evan Kohlmann, expert of the NEFA Foundation based in the United States, said that terrorist groups must also do more attention in recent years in the choice of people they accept because the U.S. secret services have become experts in relation to their recruitment methods. 
If you try to infiltrate someone in these groups, what better way than to follow its recruitment model that so many other people have already followed? Said Kohlmann. 
The model is increasingly on the Internet. 
