The results of the tests reveal persistent differences between the races 
The federal report last week on the results in mathematics has made a good news for public schools in Washington D. C. 
Although the District is still far behind the leading institutions, the report shows that the Grade 4 and Grade 5 (cm1 - cm2) are much greater progress over the past two years in cities such as Atlanta, Chicago and New York. 
But the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (National evaluation of Progress of education) is the persistent gap between the results of African-Americans and white, both local and National. 
The results of white children of Grade 4 (CM1) to WashingtonD. C. have increased over the past two years, 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500), but those of their classmates African-American increased by only three points, 209 to 212. 
The gap of success has actually increased between 2007 and 2009, from 53 to 58 points. 
The progress of African-Americans in Grade 8 (4th) remains generally constant, falling just one point, from 245 to 244. 
The result means of white has not been included in the results of the tests because the sample was not important enough. 
The overview over a period of six years is not more encouraging. 
In 2003, the gap between blacks and whites in class of Grade 4 (CM1), when the first report NAEP District was published, was 60 points (262 to 202). 
Although the results achieved by children in both groups have increased during this period, the difference was only reduced to 58 points. 
Last week, some advocates in the District have expressed concern that rising celebrated by the Director of group of educational institutions Michelle A. Rhee and Mayor Adrian M. Fenty (Democrat) were powered by white students who were already good elements. 
This would mean that we have raised the aggregate in considering the elements at the top of the scale, which is problematic and embarrassing, said Jeff Smith, director of DC Voice, a non-profit group that promotes equality in education in the District. 
I do not jump for joy for one or two points earned, "said Kwame R. Brown (related Democrat), member of the Council of D. C. and whose daughter is in Grade 4, Eaton elementary (elementary school). 
Often critical of the management style of Rhee, Brown said that the message of test results is that middle schools (colleges) of the city desperately need attention. 
Really, you always see the positive signs and I respect that. 
But the fear is that we do not spend enough time and energy to our middle schools (colleges). 
Rhee said that the District should continue to find better ways to meet the needs of students in difficulty. 
This autumn, for example, some teachers have been trained to use a new method of reading, the Wilson reading System, schoolchildren classes of end of elementary and early college who have not incorporated the foundations of reading earlier in their school and who are lagging behind their peers. 
Every day, the mathematics curriculum for grades kindergarten (kindergarten to Grade 6 (6th) focuses on the games and real life experiences, as they have been put in place in the District by former responsible Clifford Janey, which must also be credited for the progress of the NAEP reported last week. 
I simply believe that we must continue to work to provide better interventions to these students below the level of the class, said Rhee. 
Others believe that the results of the NAEP raise the question of whether Rhee can continue to raise the overall results of the system while providing money and resources for schools with less good results in order to reduce the gap. 
It is a dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a trainer of education at the University of California at Berkeley who studied the results of tests of cities. 
The conventional political solution is to devote your resources and management reforms to schools located in the poorest neighborhoods of Washington. 
Also this targeting can have political repercussions that hinder this important program. 
But the problem, of course, is that as the other superintendent of schools, it is trying to use the middle class whites and blacks. 
We focus to ensure the development of a system of good schools. 
We must strengthen our schools districts so that all families, regardless of where they come from, be assured that their children can obtain an excellent public education. 
Janey, now superintendent of schools of Newark, said in an interview this week, that one of the essential elements to reduce the gap of success étaitla duration of traditional public school, now 180 days in the District of Washington, to be in competition with the Charter schools. 
It must obtain approximately 200 days to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with the union of its teachers last year for 185 days, that it considers a "starting point" for even an increase in the next contract. 
Make higher education a promise of future 
The bus was arrested in Gettysburg College with a long whistle. 
Graciela Rodriguez, 12 years, and cligne a moment of eyes at the sight of white columns, brick facades and rolling lawns. 
The parents of Graciela had only been able to finish high school, àEl Salvador. 
Until recently, Graciela itself, who was born in Silver Spring and lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on an university campus. 
Also, when she and other students in Grade 8 (4th) group explored Gettysburg where tuition fees are $38 690 per year, his attitude was less a new student impressed that enthusiastic. 
This is where I shall study! exclaimed Graciela wishing to study medicine, while the guide heading towards the entrance of the building of science. 
Youpi, really? "she says pensive, when he said the low ratio law professor - student. 
The university of Pennsylvania was the seventh that visiting children during their journey of discovery of three days and now they had completely integrated the message: the question is not whether you go to university: 
The question is where. 
Although this question is still largely for the large number of American children born to parents Hispanic immigrants who have left the school where became parents to adolescence, they are also hundreds of thousands to benefit of university education that will enable them to enter the middle class. 
In fact, "Hispanic" second generation "on cinqpoursuit his studies at the Lycée - a notable success if one considers that both of their immigrant parents, most from Mexico or Central America, entered the United States without having completed high school. 
Their success is important, say researchers, they pave the way to future generations that will play an important role in the country. 
Researchers studying the wings say that they have a natural affinity with the school and an innate need to succeed. 
Many are also those whose parents set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools. 
The Mentoring programs also play a very important role in helping Graciela and millions of children as it to reach the university - in particular, if its efforts are regular and long-term. 
When you look at children of low-income families with parents who do not have the experience and skills to help them navigate the system, any intervention, at any time, will not help, said Patricia Gándara, researcher at Davis, University of California, who has studied the Latin American students. 
We need to provide a support network for these children from kindergarten to high school. 
The federal program that has funded the visit universities of Graciela is a good example. 
Known as the gear up (prépares you), it provides more than $300 million per year to systems of local schools to organize preparation programs at the university that begin when students from low income families are in middle school (college) and continue until the end of years of high school. 
Since 1999, the programme has been followed by more than 10 million students, with more than 60 percent entering university, according to the U. S. Department of Education. 
The ministry of Iraqi oil obtained agreements with 10 foreign oil companies 
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has managed to attract major oil companies to rebuild its infrastructure in difficulty during two auction that ended Saturday. 
The 10 agreements reached by the Ministry of Iraqi oil with foreign oil companies suggest that oil companies from China, Russia and Europe are poised to play a major role in the rehabilitation of the oil industry of Iraq, invalidated by decades of war and sanctions. 
American companies are left with an interest in only two of 10 fields auctioned. 
Seven U.S. companies had paid to participate in the second auction that began Friday. 
The only one that had set an auction has lost. 
Two American companies have obtained contracts for the fields auctioned in June. 
The low representation of American oil giants in the opening of the oil sector in Iraq has surprised analysts. 
Iraq has finally opened its doors, after six years of war, and instead of American companies, are Asian and European companies that pave the way, "said Ruba Husari, editor of the forum Iraq Oil forum, a site of information on the Internet. 
It will take a long time before another offer is made in Iraq. 
The concerns about security, corroborated by massive coordinated bombing, Tuesday, and political instability while American military troops withdraw have hampered the American oil companies, preventing them from entering with more force in Iraq, which has the third largest crude oil reserve, say analysts. 
American companies were, in some cases, disadvantaged because of their rivals, especially the Chinese and other energy companies controlled by a government, whose labour costs were significantly lower and who were more willing to take risks because they had not accountable to shareholders. 
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies to obtain contracts with the department. 
The most important American companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which have maintained strong links with the Iraqi Ministry of Oil and brought their technical advice, are left empty-handed. 
The Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the two main shareholders in two of the contracts awarded this weekend. 
The Chinese National Petroleum Corp., owned by the state, has more enchéri on contracts that other companies and is left with significant shareholdings in contracts for two main fields. 
We all know that China is becoming a major economy, as well as a technological power, said Assam Jihad, spokesman of the Ministry of Oil. 
We are confident that Chinese society will be equal to its competitors and achieve its commitments in Iraq. 
The pre-selected companies to submit auctions have made offers which were then compared to the tariff per barrel that the department agreed to pay to motivate the production above current levels for each field. 
One of the main organizers of al-Qaeda would have been killed in Pakistan 
It seems that an American missile, which hit along the border with Afghanistan has killed one of the organizers of al-qaeda's operations, this week, said Friday U. S. authorities of counter-intelligence. 
If the information is confirmed, it would be the second deadly attack against a terrorist leaders this autumn. 
Saleh al-Somali was one of two Arab men suspected to have been killed by a pair of missiles launched in their car, Tuesday, near the town of Miran Shah, in the province of North Waziristan, according to U.S. sources and Pakistani authorities in the region. 
Local authorities have said that the missiles had been fired by a pilotless aircraft of the type used by the CIA, inside the lawless tribal border of Pakistan. 
They drove a white car, heading towards the Afghan border, when the car was hit, said a member of the secret services Pakistani civilians, speaking by telephone from Miran Shah. 
The representatives of the authority said that local activists suspects rushed to place and quickly confiscated what remained of "body completely shredded ". 
It was completely impossible to local authorities to verify the identity of the victims, but the two representatives counter-terrorism officials have given evidence not specified that Somali was among the dead. 
Somali was described as one of the organizers military organizers who ran the al-Qaeda terrorist operations group outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region. 
Its role was to organize conspiracies around the world, "said one of the authorities who wished to remain anonymous, citing the sensitive nature of air strikes inside Pakistani territory. 
Given its central role, this probably included conspiracies of attacks against the United States and Europe. 
It followed the strategic leaders of al-Qaeda and has translated into action plans for possible terrorist attacks. 
A second representative of the American authority said that Somali had progressed rapidly in the ranks of al-Qaida "s and had very good relations with other extremist groups in the region. 
It is perhaps not known to the general public, but this does not diminish the threat It poses for us and our allies, "said the second official representative. 
If his death is confirmed, Somali would be the second important figure of al-Qaeda or the second leader Taliban killed since September, when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, leader of a faction of militants in the tribal belt, as well as three other operators. 
The pace of attacks carried out by CIA drones has declined since the summer, about six operations per month to two, according to the figures given by the Long War Journal, a Web site tempered by a non-profit group. 
This decline is perhaps due to improved tactics of terrorist groups that have progressed to reduce their vulnerability while killing also ruthlessly suspected informants, says the site. 
The U.N. special envoy in Kabul withdrew 
The U.N. special envoy in Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said Friday that he would resign from his post in March, at the end of a tumultuous tenure marred by allegations of corruption extent during the presidential elections supported by the United Nations. 
The departure of Eide comes at a time when the Obama administration decided to send 30, 000 additional troops in Afghanistan. 
The U.N. envoy said that he supported this increase, but he expressed concern about the timetable for a withdrawal of troops that would begin in 18 months and that would force the other NATO governments to withdraw their forces. 
We need to accelerate the development of our security forces in Afghanistan, send the right signal to Afghans and remind them that they can have confidence in the international community, "said Eide in a telephone interview from Kabul. 
Our commitment must be long-term. 
The Norwegian diplomat has also urged the U.S. and other military powers to increase the number of international staff assisting the political transition in Afghanistan. 
The military increase must be copied by civilians, he said. 
Eide said he did not resign but that it would respect the commitment that he made to his family in March, will spend two years in Kabul. 
He said that he wanted to prevent the United Nations. 
The Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon now knows that he has time to find a replacement. 
I simply said that it was better to start looking for my replacement, said Eide. 
When I came here, there was a gap of two months between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival. 
According to the representatives of the United Nations, Ban has already begun to seek a replacement. 
The representatives claim that the name of Staffan di Mistura was quoted; it is a citizen Italo-Suisse recently chaired an U.N. mission in Baghdad and Jean-Marie Guéhenno, a Frenchman who has previously led the peacekeeping operations of the United Nations. 
The reputation of Eide in Afghanistan has been put to the test after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, was accused in September, President Hamid Karzai during the presidential elections and to conceal evidence of massive electoral fraud. 
Eide denied these allegations but he said that the accusations of Galbraith - which has been thanked - "have damaged the mission because there was already a good dose of scepticism as regards the international observation of éléctions ". 
Eide said that he had proposed the appointment of a civilian representative to coordinate the rescue of American forces in Afghanistan. 
He also urged the United Nations to allow his successor to hire more staff from the United States and other Western countries that it is attributed to the mission in Afghanistan, saying that this would give them more confidence about how their money is spent. 
Eide has expressed his frustration about the limits of its powers in Afghanistan, saying that the heavy hiring regulations of the United Nations hindered its ability to bring new talent. 
The rules of The United Nations are such that I could not recruit only one person since May, he said. 
It is catastrophic and it cannot last. 
Gates: Iran must undergo additional sanctions 
The Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates said Friday that world powers would soon impose "significant additional sanctions" on Iran because of its inability to engage in talks on the nuclear ambitions. 
Gates, speaking before a crowd of 300 American soldiers in northern Iraq, during a visit to a week in war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, has dédramatisé the possibility of military action against the Islamic Republic. 
There is no good option in Iran, he said, in response to the question of a soldier on the possibility of such an outcome. 
One of the things that weighs me most is that if I learned one thing in Iraq over the past six years, it is the unpredictable inherent in the war. 
The Obama administration considers a set of sanctions that target the military and political elite in Iran, but Gates has reported that some of these sanctions could also affect the Iranians in the street. 
He said that "a set of incentives and punishments" might be needed to persuade the Iranian government that it would in fact less good security with nuclear weapons "because" his people would suffer greatly "of these sanctions. 
Friday, in a statement from the White House spokesman, Robert Gibbs, the administration has joined the European leaders in warning that Iran will face consequences "probable" if it does not bring its nuclear program in full compliance with the U.N. Security Council and its supervisory body, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). 
Iran continues to say that he wants to develop its nuclear experience only in a peaceful purposes. 
In the talks in Geneva on 1 October, he indicated that it would resume dialogue on the reduction of its nuclear programme and agreed to give up a significant part of its storage of enriched uranium in exchange for fuel desperately needed for a medical research reactor. 
The administration has prompted such an agreement, way to develop a confidence on both sides and to save time for negotiations. 
Since then, Iran appears to be away from attempts to agreement - in part, experts say, because the Iranian leadership is divided on whether or not to engage with the United States. 
Frankly, in my view, the stiffening of Iran with some of the proposals of the international community to which they had in fact given their agreement in early October, prompted the international community, including the Russians and the Chinese, to join what they had not considered, in terms of significant additional sanctions against the Iranians, said Gates. 
President Obama has set a December 31 deadline for Iran to respond to proposals, before he turned to other options, including the continuation of what Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called "increased sanctions ". 
In a statement Thursday in New York, the mission of Iran to the United Nations has denounced what it calls "baseless allegations" of some members of the Security Council on Iran's nuclear activities of Iran and said that she agreed to continue talks with the United States and five other major world powers, "in order to obtain a satisfactory solution in the long term ". 
Gates, who was to return to Washington late Friday, met in the morning, Iraqi Prime Minister, Nouri al-Maliki, before flying to the oil rich region of Kurdish to derencontrer troops to Kirkuk, Kurdish and Irbil. 
Tensions persist between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq, particularly concerning the borders, property rights and the sharing of income. 
Gates has urged both sides to reduce the potential conflict in order to avoid any delays of U.S. plans to reduce the number of American troops, 115 000 to 50 000 before the end of August. 
Gates also wishes to calm the anxiety of Kurds concerning the withdrawal pending. The American authorities have cited Gates saying to Massoud Barzani, president of the Kurdistan regional government: "We will preserve your security, your prosperity and your autonomy within an unified Iraq ". 
We will not abandon you. " 
In China, a change of direction 
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by poster of propaganda lecturing, "Mother Earth is too tired to accommodate more children" and "a baby, this is a grave in more ". 
They have learned the lesson that the authorities of the Government of Shanghai, alarmed by the lack of birth rate of their city and the ageing of the population, have radically changed direction this summer and began to encourage young couples to have more than one child; their reaction was instantaneous and firm: never. 
We have already given all our time and energy to one child. 
There is no second, said Wang, 31, director of human resources and has a son of 8 months. 
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, creating two generations of children unique notoriously with good cheeks and spoiled, dubbed "little emperors ", a crisis of the population threatens the country. 
According to the UN, the average birth rate fell from 1.8 children per couple compared to six when the policy was implemented. 
The distribution of the population, while it is expected that the number of residents aged 60 and over will explode, 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. This figure is well above the overall average of about 20 percent. 
This imbalance is even worse in the rich coastal cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai. 
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for nearly 22 percent of the population of residents registered in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple. 
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission (Commission of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning) said that the fertile couples to have babies in order "to help reduce the proportion of the aging Population and prevent a lack of manpower in the future ". 
Shanghai is on the verge of becoming "too old - but not as rich, however - that developed countries such as Japan and Sweden," she said. 
A gradual mitigation 
In the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is to this day, without doubt, the most controversial requirement introduced by the communist government. 
Couples who violate this policy may have to pay huge fines - up to three times their annual income - and suffer discrimination in the workplace. 
The Chinese authorities have attributed to the police on duty to help the country to avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while lawyers for human rights have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy. 
In rural areas, some representatives of the authority have forced pregnant women a second child to have abortions. 
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to a ratio boys - girls abnormally high. 
In recent years, the authorities of the population have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy. 
In 2004, they have given more exceptions to the rule - including for residents of cities, members of ethnic minorities and the cases in which men and women are already children unique - and in 2007, they have softened much of their slogans hard. 
Qiao Xiaochun, professor at the Institute of Population Research (Institute of Population Research), at Peking University, said that the central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner is an only child. 
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births. 
In no time, the posters encouraging families to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations retailer who has the right to have a second child and how to apply for authorization. 
The city government has dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples at home, and slipping leaflets under their door. 
He has also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child. 
According to the head of family planning, the response has been disappointing. 
Disappointing response 
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for records of couples wanting a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban district reported that there was no change. 
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115 000 inhabitants, for example, is always that four to five requests per month. 
Officials in Shanghai, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city, in 2010, is still expected to be only about 165 000 - slightly higher than 2009 but lower than 2008. 
Feng Juying, Head of the Committee of family planning in the municipality of Caolu of Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children. 
They want to fill their first child, she said. 
Yang Jiawei, 27 years and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26 years, said that they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed. 
But like many Chinese, they have only the minimum health insurance and life assurance given by the government. 
Without a social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible. 
The Western mistakenly see that the one-child policy is a problem of rights, "said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child. 
It is true, we stole the chance to have more than one child. 
But the problem is not only the law. 
It is money. 
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation. 
Wang, human resources, said she wanted a single child because it was an itself. "We were the centre of the family and had used that everyone cares." 
We do not have the habit of taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others. " 
Chen Zijian, 42 years and owner of a translation the said more bluntly. 
For couples working at two, middle class, which restrict the birth rate, he says, it must be selfish pourbien succeed. 
The People of 20 or 30 years have grown up seeing their parents fight in the early days of China capitalist and do not want to have themselves this way of life, "he says. 
Even one child asks a lot of time his parents, he says. 
A mother must abandon at least two years of her social life. 
Then there are the problems of space - "you must change your apartment" - and planning - "When your child has only 9 months, you need to write his CV for a place in the best mother tongue." 
Most of his friends are willing to this experience once, said Chen, but not two. 
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, "he says. 
We do not want to make too many sacrifices. 
The group of the United Nations has plans for reducing emissions 
The climate conference, sponsored by the United nations - characterized so far by postings disorganized and mutual recriminations - is back under the spotlight Friday, due to the publication of a document outlining the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations supporting most of the burden in the coming years. 
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, stressed the remaining obstacles, as much as it has informed the path to take. 
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that lack of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving next week in Copenhagen. 
Written by a special working group of the United Nations, the text does not say how rich countries would give the poor to withstand global warming, short and long term. 
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how the developed economies and emerging economies could reduce their production of carbon and what would be the upper limit of the increase in global temperature that those responsible would be willing to tolerate. 
It gives great flexibility in the process, said John Coequyt, Representative of the Sierra Club. 
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has written six pages of the document, studied a text of negotiations of 180 pages to focus on what has described the Secretary-General executive on climate change, Yvo de Boer, as "the full picture ". 
It shows the guidelines of a possible agreement in which the industrial nations collectively reduce their emissions in 2020, from 25 to 45 percent compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce emissions by 15 to 30 percent. 
Together, the countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent for 2050. 
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations, Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change - to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation. 
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week. 
Todd Stern, Representative of the United States to the negotiating climate has rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, in comparison with the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed countries. 
This change is the signal that the Obama administration becomes harder to China that the Bush administration has been two years ago. 
The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text does not enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by outside observers. 
Stern made his comments a hour after the Chinese deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei has said that the U.S. chief negotiator, lacked "common sense ", was" extremely irresponsible "for having said earlier in the week that the U.S. would not help financially China to combat global warming. 
With the future economic trajectories of major world powers involved, defects are both within the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies. 
The current battle is more the rescue of individual economies that the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States querellant on their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen countries most influential ignore scientific imperatives to act more boldly. 
Ricardo ulate, a delegate of Costa Rica, stated that it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of the reduction of greenhouse gases, even if the vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make the major emitters accountable for their actions. 
It is really a game in which has developed a new economic hegemony, said ulate, which is also on the climate adviser for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International. 
Some of these countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they would continue to put pressure to obtain a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants say that negotiations will lead to a minimum, a political agreement. 
The Alliance of Small Island States which brings together 43 members, has drafted a proposal for a treaty of 24 pages, early Friday morning. 
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of unit climate of the European Commission, said that the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the political process complete ", in part by what they are now unified and they seek to emerging economies such as China and India, to act. 
The debates have become a matter of urgency, while delegates focused on the fact that they should solve most problems pending before the heads of government come to an agreement. 
High-level officials such as the Minister of the environment, Jairam Ramesh Indian and Chinese Vice-Minister descended from their plane and rushed into the building of the Bella Center to attend meetings in camera and conferences of information, in order to make claims that will be reviewed during the following week. 
The true image of the gathering - during which 13, 000 people entering and exiting the Palais des Congrès every day - activists guitar players are nocturnal entertainment mocking of countries that they betray and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by emails - constitutes a real challenge. 
The intensity is increasing: almost all key ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of governments will be in Copenhagen. 
We are entering the big boys, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy of Conservation International. 
Lorries arrive. 
In Britain, the first train to 225 km/h will redefine the syndrome Monday 
A 5h13, Monday morning, a whistle percera night to signal the start of a train that will mark a revolution of transport in Britain. 
The first high-speed commuter train the country will reach 225 km / h, whereas it filera of Ashford, in Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes. 
Lord Adonis, the Transport Minister, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes aboard the first commuter train Javelin outside London. 
He hoped that the new service will allow Britain to integrate an international network of fast trains and reliable and will link the large conurbations of the Midlands, North and Scotland in London. 
The small holes lost become commuter cities successful business travel will be much less long and the passage of the plane and the car to the train will reduce national emissions of carbon while reducing congestion on the roads. 
In theory, the three main political parties adhering to this project. 
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new rail network, the battle of planning inevitable and fears of dangers to the environment may curb high-speed lines. 
According to the Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company established in January to achieve for the government a feasibility report, will make his document to Lord Adonis on 30 December. 
It will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage for the high-speed network. 
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn within five metres of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment can be controversial. 
In the campaign, the plan will be drawn up to 25 metres of the final itinerary. 
It is also expected that HS2 presents three options for a high-speed network more towards the north. 
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring. 
The preferred options are put forward in a configuration in Y for which a high-speed line will go to the West Midlands. 
The line split into two at or near Birmingham, with a branch from west Pennines àManchester and Scotland and another towards the northeast, Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne. 
A single line through Scotland. 
"It seems that this will be the best option of performance" said a professional rail. 
When this is completed, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes. 
The first part, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to travel a hour now. 
The proposals will allow the train to travel to 400km / h, making the UK network the fastest in the world. 
The original route is designed to allow trains to 400m in length and can carry 1100 people. 
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on a line London - Birmingham. 
A terminal that can accommodate 20, 000 passengers per hour would be necessary. 
Given the constraints of space, it is anticipated that an existing station will be expanded to receive the high-speed network. 
The rail industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility. 
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he feels that the project must be put in place, but public consultations longer and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be taken before a general election. 
Even if it launches the machine, the network will be built part by part. 
The trains will initially be forced to drive out of high-speed lines on existing track north of Birmingham, retaining journey times between London and Scotland than three hours. 
This solution seems to be the best to ensure passage of trains, constituting a reference point for the rail revolution. 
