Alan Duncan, senior Tory member of parliament, charged the taxpayer thousands of pounds per year to reimburse the cost of an Orangerie that it has built in his home in his constituency. 
The head of the party that has been demoted by David Cameron for complaining that members of parliament were "maintained ", has increased its loan of £75, 000 to build an extension in oak at his second home in Rutland. 
He had been authorized to pay the additional interest, amounting to hundreds of pounds per month, to the taxpayer. 
The authorities have received complaints at the time and have not been interviewed by Sir Thomas Legg, who has a control of expenditure. Last night, Mr Duncan said that complaints could not be "clearer or more simple ". 
Mr Duncan, one of the richest members of parliament, is the owner of a two-storey house in a village in his constituency of Rutland - Melton. 
The neighbouring houses were sold for nearly a million pounds. 
The ground floor includes a kitchen, a living room and dining room, but the office of emoluments asserts that Mr. Duncan needed more space. 
Last year, he added a porch at home, describing in its plans as an orange. 
The neighbours describe it as a "porch for pleasure ". 
It has not been asked Mr Duncan to give an explanation for the increase in borrowing during a recent investigation made by the Committee of Privileges and standards of the Commons, on its loan provisions. 
The Committee has cleared last month of any accusation of non-compliance with the rules, after an investigation into his expenses. 
In 2004, Mr Duncan has changed the legal certainty of borrowing of GBP 271.406 of his property in London at home in his constituency that he bought in 1991, the year before becoming a member of parliament. 
The documents published this week show that Mr Duncan claimed approximately £1, 400 per month of interest loan until March last year. 
In April, its applications have increased by more than 1, 800 GBP per month. 
The interest rate on the loan RBS of Mr Duncan has not been changed at that time, suggesting that all increases were intended to finance the borrowing of £75, 000. 
The interest rate standard variable RBS rose from 7.94 percent in December 2007 to 4 percent in March this year, without moving since then. 
The last publication of Commons authorities shows that Mr Duncan continued to ask 1.250 GBP in May. 
Mr Duncan lost his position as head of the shadow cabinet in September, after a journalist in coverage was allegedly filmed saying that members of parliament were to survive "on budget" after the expenses scandal. 
"In fact, it is now national, you must live" on budget "and you are treated as" m... " 
