USA: a sign of sarcophagus belonged to Zola awarded $1.5 million 
A panel of Roman sarcophagus belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was awarded Thursday $1.5 million, well above its estimate, announced the art dealer Sotheby's. 
This sign before two metres long on 63 cm high, dating from the third century AD, was estimated at between 150, 000 and 250, 000 dollars. 
The marble "representing four scenes dionysiaques in a sophisticated architectural decor, surrounded by satyres and bacchantes, is a rare piece, there are only four or five in the world," explained to AFP Tuesday Florent Heintz, vice-president of the auction of art of ancient Roman and Egyptian among Sotheby's. 
It was sold among a hundred lots. 
The sale is still ongoing but this lot is certainly the one on which most buyers outbidding so far, indicated to AFP a Sotheby's spokesman, Dan Abernethy. 
The discovery of the acquisition of this marble by Emile Zola back in a few days. 
The panel has remained almost 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the family Borghese, then became successively among the French actress Cécile Sorel, who had an element of his bathtub in her Parisian mansion, and Paul Reynaud, Minister under the Third Republic in France and briefly Council president before the accession to power of Marshal Pétain. 
Remained a grey area of fifty years. 
In searching the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz has discovered that this sign was part of a "succession Emile Zola" opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and the epic "Rougon-Macquart ". 
