I called for the abandonment of charges here and now, said Mr. Hummel, before adding that the behaviour of the judge in the case at the time, Laurence Rittenband, "was cold in the back ". 
According to him, the Judge Rittenband - died since - would have discussed, before making his sentence, with a prosecutor who told him that Roman Polanski deserved the prison - which is a serious lack of procedure. 
This discussion was revealed in the documentary "Roman Polanski: wanted and desired" (Roman Polanski, sought and desired), the lips of the prosecutor, David Wells. 
But Mr Wells had finally declared late September have "lied" to the author of the documentary. 
If the court refuses to abandon the prosecution, Mr. Hummel has demanded a trial, which would allow him to present the evidence of his arguments. 
The prosecution has reiterated the arguments already developed in the first instance, namely that no abandonment charges could be seriously considered as Roman Polanski would not be before the court. 
The filmmaker, aged 76, had fled the United States in 1978, before the sentencing, for "illegal sexual relations" with a minor of 13 years. 
It has never set foot in the United States since. 
