More than a footnote on Herta Müller 
It is by these words "Arrival in Germany and it is beautiful, almost more control..." that begins a work of the poet Werner Söllner, in which he dealt with in snippets of disturbing sentences, the experiences of a dissident arrived in Germany who won freedom but lost at the same time its linguistic territory. 
Werner Söllner, born in 1951 to Banat in Romania, was first professor of German and English in Bucharest and, subsequently, director of collection in a publishing house for youth before moving to Frankfurt am Main. 
Söllner received various literary prizes; in 1993 he was the highly coveted chair of poetry of Goethe University in Frankfurt and since 2002 he is director of the forum of literature of Hesse in the house of artist Mousonturm in Frankfurt. 
He has done a lot of him in circles not literary last Tuesday, at a conference in Munich, whose theme was "the German literature in Romania in the mirror and the distorting mirror of your files Securitate ". 
Visibly destabilized and embarrassed, Söllner made a statement in which he acknowledged to his fellow writers germano-roumains as Richard Wagner, William Totok, Franz Hodjak, and Helmuth Frauendorfer that he had worked as an informant for the Securitate police policy. 
Söllner received in 1989 the price of the German language together with some of the participants. 
The trials of enrolment insidiously in 1971. 
I am, therefore, concludes Söllner "someone who has not sufficiently stood auxessais intimidation of the Securitate." 
The poet Werner Söllner is the informant Walter (Im Walter). 
Almost simultaneously with the honoration Nobel Prize for Herta Müller and his literary copies with the mechanisms of power of the dictatorship, the literary scene is shaken and in particular the community of German authors from Romania, in a case which clearly shows the pitfalls and baseness of a political system, based on police surveillance and espionage. 
Werner Söllner is, as far as we can tell from the current knowledge, not only guilty but also victim. 
In his own Securitate file, Im Walter played a role, provides specialist literature Michael Markel after the confession of Söllner and it refers to the positive influence of Im Walter who had interceded In his favour. 
"He had been drawn from all difficult situations at the time," according to Markel. 
Markel has felt the need moralde make this comment. 
The form in which Söllner made his statement and before the public was unexpected, however the admission of a former dissident its collaboration with the Romanian secret services is in fact, not so surprising. 
Germany is a reserve for the spies of the Securitate had already written Herta Müller in July in the journal "Die Zeit ", having read the 914 pages of his own record. 
It can be assumed that the victims have made speculation and sometimes have guessed what real names were hiding last names borrowing Sorin, Voicu and Walter. 
Unlike Germany where the consultation of the Stasi files is a reliable process, the attitude to the legacy of the Securitate files is still very confused. 
A systematic clarification was constantly frustrated and slowed in past years. 
It was only in 1999 that a national council corresponding to the institution Birthler was created to work with the assimilation of Archives of the Securitate (CNSAS) but the return of files rather dragged since. 
Since 2005 there is a law that defines the management of archives. 
The influence of former members of the Securitate in Romania is still very great, is confirmed by an interview with a former head of the Securitate of Temesvar who, after the announcement of the award of the Nobel Prize to Herta Müller, expressed very dismissive of the winner. 
She had a psychosis, and ultimately it had questioned only once. 
The infamy of power felt able to speak here, without any gene, under the guise of freedom of expression. 
Certainly, many questions are associated with the case Söllner as happens so often in a context of guilt hidden. 
Why now? Which has been despoiled? The weighted response from listeners, the admission of Söllner, hope that the result of this chapter will be defined more by a thirst for knowledge that by accusations and a sense of shame. 
On the genesis of the work of Herta Müller, who received the Nobel Prize yesterday, it is more than a footnote. 
