The worlds of dream 
Some see, awake, images and hear voices that nobody else sees or hears. 
It is not only among the mental patients, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between fantasy and reality blur. 
As these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is going very well. 
When we are lying in our rooms clouded, we can do without hindrance to the dreams and wildest fantasies. 
However, awake, experienced dream, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly reputation in our western world to be crazy or drugged, or at least to be an original. 
Such images and voices do not appear in the mental patients or under the influence of drugs. 
It is our imagination that is at stake: It is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, but sometimes prompts the boundaries between the dream, madness and reality to merge. 
A state of arousal aware, taking the form of a dream, may be in various forms, in the best case it is called visions, at worst madness. 
But even if the trigger and the effect differ, visions of the mystical Hildegard von Bingen, drug experiences of the prophet of New Age Carlos Castaneda, the latter of chamanes, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to process very similar. 
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance, substances neurotransmettrices brain - first and foremost the dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achétylcholine - breaks down and that the interaction between the different parts of the brain is disrupted. 
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during a schizophrenic psychosis. 
The force of attraction land has more power on the person. 
Since antiquity, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and the dream. 
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of rêve-éveillé; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, found in 1861 "a great similarity between madness and the dream," Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all irregularities, imagination, delusions and illusions sensory who composed ". 
We are in autumn 2001 when Henning T turns into a comic strip. 
His body is in two dimensions to the garish colours. 
The attraction land has more power over him, to the ceiling. 
He feels a coup. 
Behind him creatures of devil ailées, grimaçantes, mouth bloodied, showing the teeth. 
They continue, give him kicking with heavy boots, the cast against the walls, he feels pain throughout the body. 
The thundering voice, nasty, howl, leaving the walls and radio. 
It can no longer bear those voices who insult and humiliate. 
Henning T. pulled two cables of its stereo, in fact a loop and attached to a hook attached to the ceiling. 
It is on a baffle and happens the loop around the neck. 
He jumps. 
The loop stands out. 
That you serve as a lesson, shout the voice in a chorus to extract the eardrum. "in a clinic and fais-toi treat!" 
Today Henning T. 40 years ago, he lived six acute psychosis, the last date of 2 years, the first in nearly 20 years. 
It was triggered by LSD. 
The diagnosis: psychosis schizo-affective, paranoid, furthermore it is maniaco-dépressif, he takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia. 
He has learned to live with his illness, he is married for three years. 
During the psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despair. 
The illusions are a cruel reality. 
About one percent of the population suffers at least once in her life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics is the most common illness after the depression. 
In a crisis of schizophrenia, people can no longer make the difference between the internal world and the outside world, they find themselves in a state of hyper excitation, that they may suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution. 
It is very common to hear voices - voices command, which elicited comments or dialogue. 
The optical hallucinations are not rare. 
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the trivial, the brain can no longer filter disruptive signals, the aware is drowned in the sensations. 
Just as the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies outcome of deeper layers of conscience. 
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the Department of Psychiatry Chu in Heidelberg (Allgemeine Psychiatry im Universitätsklinikum). 
The schizophrenic is located in the centre of the situation, meaning focused on him. 
At the same time it is found in a passive role, it is like a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively. 
That is why the schizophrenia often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated. 
In general they do not have the opportunity to adjust the reality, the illusions are a cruel reality, wake up is excluded. 
To experience once in her life of a hallucination. 
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is seen during the psychosis, is fundamentally retained ". 
The thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of lived in a real framework. 
Why does our brain this kind of antics, is still a mystery to researchers. 
Exceptional situations can bring everyone to lose momentarily the perception of reality, according to Fuchs. 
But only a small number of people develop a psychosis. 
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determinants. 
The researchers speculate that the persons concerned are tiny brain damage. 
It is assumed that the neuronale maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example, by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs. 
But what remains unexplained is how the neural system occurs and also the fact that it is not for many years. 
Environmental factors also play a role - stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger of psychosis, if there is a predisposition. 
Similarly the hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters. 
When our brain heats. 
This is crazy, says professor of psychology Erich Kasten of Lübeck is that the psychotic suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to undo while others buy drugs very expensive to obtain. 
The perception pleasant or unpleasant illusions is often just a matter of perspective. 
Kasten brings together for ten years reports of hallucinations and phenomena of images illusory: last year he published his findings in a book entitled "the unreal world in our heads ". 
The hallucinations are part of concomitant phenomena typical psychoses but also an impressive number of many other diseases. 
They include psychological problems such as borderline or depression but also the migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma. 
It is surprising that in certain conditions even the brains of healthy people is subject to hallucinations. 
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that normally are inhibited. 
They take form when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions, are hyperactives or not sufficiently refrénées; when our brain heats but also when there is lack of stimulation. 
The drugs can trigger this state as a brain injury or psychosis. 
But also the lack of stimulus, stress, sorrows of love or other mental states exceptional. 
In recent studies, a third of participants acknowledged having made at least once in her life experience a hallucination. 
In summer 2005 Sarah K. 16 years ago, she lives a small town in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania and it goes to high school. 
A young girl to normal indeed. 
If there was not the images and voices. 
During the recess, sometimes a young boy, thin, with long hair, wish him the floor. 
When she replied his comrades watch, surprised - no one else sees or hears this boy. 
They believe that this girl timid is a lunatic but Sarah K does not dream, it is certain. 
She is awake, hears and sees the boy as she sees and hears the girl who is sitting next to her on the bench. 
It can even see its presence temporarily. 
It is a good feeling, she found this young sympathetic. 
Am I mad?, wondered sometimes. 
But she knows that this young and other visions are not real and they will disappear again. 
The night appearances are, in general, frightening. 
Often the visions are cumbersome. 
When it is in class, sometimes it can follow the course because the teacher is just being present a new student in his eyes and ears When it is invisible to others and that the professor is clearly explain the equations in table. 
The night appearances are, in general, frightening. 
When, in the darkness of his room, it expects the sleep that comes too rarely and far too late, it often cannot make the distinction if she is awake or dream already, if the images she sees, faces grimaçants or the girl with bloody cuts on his arms and legs are before its eyes open or closed. 
Let me quiet, Cree to these creatures. 
It does not speak or his parents or friends, they would take to a mad. 
Fall 2009. Sarah K. has now 20 years. 
She had her ferry last year and she lives with her friend. 
A year ago the hallucinations have ceased. 
Since it came into contact via the Internet with the psychologist Kasten she knows very well that it is not crazy. 
The madness is also a work of art of despair. 
When someone is socially isolated or has not sufficient incentives, the probability is high that he has hallucinations after a certain time. 
I assume that the brain is not busy enough, ensures that there is animation. 
Sarah K., single girl, was afraid of other children when she was small and often played alone. 
Its hallucinations began when she learned to 13 years, the man she called Daddy, since it was in age to think, was not his real father. 
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual hallucinations and acoustic, and the impressions and noise, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to differentiate between the illusion and reality. "every experience ", according to Kasten" takes place in the brain, the reality is formed from there. 
The hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, that is why they seem so real. " 
For Kasten, nocturnal dreams are also a form of hallucination. 
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those in acute psychosis. 
Unlike the schizophrenic, mentally healthy person is able to recognize that the fantasies are not real images. 
That is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish the hallucinations as a particular talent. 
There is only a step between the dream and the hallucination. 
In our world too focused on the conscience has unfortunately quickly tend to take the imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief medical officer of the Clinical psychiatry and psychotherapy hospital Florence Nightingale in Düsseldorf. 
A psychosis is a serious disease, painful but which also contains something positive, creator - madness is a work of art of despair. 
Schmidt-degenhard has studied the form of so-called oniroïde experience, a particular form of the conscience stirred by the dream. 
The experienced oniroïdes are very complex semi-rêves which are seen as real by the lives and that it cannot differentiate the dream even when it is in a state of awakening. 
The state of consciousness oniroïde occurs during a trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathie which fully aware, experience a paralysis engine. 
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total inability and sustainable to move, it replaces the real situation that affects his life, by his own imaginary world that is divorced from reality. 
It is a state of mental boundary between the dream and the hallucination. 
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world but the real situation is represented in the imagination. 
It is, in fact, a form of means and interpretation, in a situation itself intolerable, organizational capacity that is given to us men, not to sink into the none of the loss of consciousness. 
Everything is real even later in the memories. 
The Zurichois Peter Cornelius Classen, art historian also describes his experiences oniroïdes in his book "change of heart" as action to safeguard the soul. 
He was 49 years, when his conscious part for a trip of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed a transplant; meanwhile, his body was sentenced to remain motionless in resuscitation. 
Claussen plunges into a world that it has created from scratch, visit foreign travel in time. It is old man bed in a sanatorium rail, a robot at his bedside ensuring on his health. 
He lives in the middle ages of noble who manufacture drugs based on blood. 
It is abducted by a Greek motorcycle who takes in his country, he surfing with his hospital bed in the firn Alps and meeting a Korean mafia. 
It is absorbed completely in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories. 
According to Claussen these domestic trips are fundamentally different from any dream. 
The dream is a completely different state, he wrote in describing what he lived. 
Instead of dreams, memories from mental travel are extremely clear and very detailed even years later. 
We can even say that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the real experience. 
The intensity of this lived shattered the horizon of our other everyday experiences, according to the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard. 
Ultimately, the oniroïdes, psychoses, hallucinations and experiences we show how our internal representations of external reality are fragile even in eve. 
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality." 
An experience that can also be quite rewarding. 
