Acciona dispute its first motorway in Australia to Hochtief and Bouygues 
Acciona is fighting for its first motorway concession in Australia, market on which it is already working as a business manager of energy and water. 
The site at stake is a tunnel estimated at 1 700 million Australian dollars (around euros 1 047 million). 
The French company Bouygues and the German company Hochtief are its rivals. 
A tunnel 5 kilometres long in the Australian city of Brisbane, on the East Coast, such is the option to allow Acciona to settle in the country as a company of public works and dealer of motorways. 
The mayor of the city wants to have by the end of 2014. 
Having chosen the public / private partnership (PPP for its initials in English) to complete the project, in the framework of a business plan under the tutelage of Erns Young, local administration already has a list of finalists who will be responsible for the construction and operation of the toll. 
Pending the presentation of their bids in May, the planned investment amounts to 1 700 million Australian dollars (around euros 1 047 million) and in the last phase will face three consortia, with a significant presence of European manufacturers. 
The group called Transcity is led by Acciona, only Spanish company in smooth, and his associates are MDBs and Ghella. 
The first is one of the largest manufacturers Australian, while the second, installed in Italy, is one of the largest European specialists to work underground. 
Against the team of Acciona, shoe the consortium Northern Direct, with the presence of the British firm Laing O'Rourke, manager Australian infrastructure Transfield and the French manufacturer group Bouygues. 
The third and final consortium that has passed the test is LBRJV, whose capital is shared between the Australian Leighton (a subsidiary of the German manufacturer Hochtief, which has in turn the participation of GBA), another local company, Baulderstone (ownership of the German group Bilfinger Berger) and the Welsh company specializing in public works, Razel. 
The Australian market infrastructure promises of major projects and privatisation, but enter represents a great difficulty, if not through The acquisition of a local construction company. 
A strategy that followed the companies Hochtief and Bilfinger, already mentioned, in addition to their Asian references, and which is still a step not validated for the Spanish giants of the sector. 
GBA is just to win a place on this market by its participation of 30% in Hochtief, owner of Leighton. 
Active millionaires 
Acciona on a geographical area of the utmost importance for the sector, on which it already has a large presence through its energy supplier and activity in the sector desalination. 
Among other assets, it has the largest wind farm, Waubra (192 MW) in Victoria, and directs the grouping of companies to build and manage the dessalinisateur of Adelaide, with a budget of 700 million. 
It now intends to consolidate these two areas and take advantage of synergies to enter the markets of the construction and management of infrastructure. 
The road toll underground, promoted by the Office of infrastructure of the city of Brisbane and the Northern Link (north), is called upon to Link the highway Toowong western peripheral route to Kelvin Grove (see map), by 4 kilometres of tunnel. It is the largest existing project to reduce traffic congestion in Brisbane. 
The timetable set by the administration indicates that the auction will take place during the summer of 2010 and that the work will begin in December of next year. 
Despite the fact that this toll road will be open to traffic late 2014, it is not anticipated that the site is completed before 2016. 
The tunnel has begun to be designed in 2005. 
It will include two times two lanes, an electronic toll system and a complex ventilation system. 
The Queensland Government will provide 500 million Australian dollars (308 million euros) for its funding. 
